\subsection*{12.6 Dispersion and Variation}

The degree to which numerical data tend to spread adout an average value is called the variation or dispersion of the data. Yarious measures of dispersion or variation are available.

\subsection*{12.6.1 Mean Deviation}

The mean deviation or average deviation of a set of $N$ numbers $X_{1}, X_{2}, \ldots, X_{N}$ is defined by:/*
$$\text { Mean Deviaion }=\bar{X}=\frac{\sum_{\mathrm{j}=1}^{\mathrm{N}}\left|X_{j}-\bar{X}\right|}{N}$$

\section*{Example:}

Find the mean deviation of the set of numbers $2,3,6,8,11$.

\section*{Solution:}

Arithmetic Mean $=\bar{X}=\frac{2+3+6+8+11}{5}=6$
$$\begin{aligned}
\text { Mean Deviation (MD) } & =\frac{|2-6|+|3-6|+|6-6|+|8-6|+|11-6|}{5} \\
& =\frac{|-4|+|-3|+|0|+|2|+|5|}{5} \\
& =\frac{4+3+0+2+5}{5}=2.8
\end{aligned}$$

If $X_{1}, X_{2}, \ldots, X_{K}$ occur with frequencies $f_{1}, f_{2}, f_{3}, \ldots, f_{k}$ respectively, the mean deviation can be written as :

Mean Deviation $=\frac{\sum_{j=1}^{K} f_{j}\left|X_{j}-\bar{X}\right|}{N}$
where $N=\sum_{j=1}^{K} f_{j}=\sum \mathrm{f}_{\mathrm{j}}$

This form is useful for grouped data where the $X_{j}$ 's represent class marks and the $\mathrm{f}_{\mathrm{j}}$ 's are the corresponding frequencies.

\subsection*{12.6.2 The Standard Deviation}

The standard deviation of a set of N numbers $\mathrm{X}_{1}, \mathrm{X}_{2}, \ldots, \mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{K}}$ is denoted by SD and is defined by
$$\begin{aligned}
& =\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N} f_{j}\left(X_{j}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}{N}} \\
& =\sqrt{\frac{\sum(X-\bar{X})^{2}}{N}} \\
& =\sqrt{\frac{\sum X}{N}-\bar{X}^{2}}
\end{aligned}$$

If $X_{1}, X_{2}, \ldots, X_{K}$ occur, ith irequencies $f_{1}, f_{2}, \ldots, f_{K}$ respectively, the standard deviation can be written as:
$$\begin{aligned}
\text { SD } & =\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{K} f_{j}\left(X_{j}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}{N}} \\
& =\sqrt{\frac{\sum f(X-\bar{X})^{2}}{N}} \\
& =\sqrt{\frac{\sum f^{2}}{N}-\bar{X}^{2}} \\
\text { where } N & =\sum_{i=1}^{K} f_{i}=\sum f
\end{aligned}$$

This form is useful for grouped data.

\subsection*{12.6.3 The Variance}

The variance of a set N numbers $\mathrm{X}_{1}, \mathrm{X}_{2}, \ldots, \mathrm{X}_{\mathrm{K}}$ is defined as the square of the standard deviation and is thus given by
$$\begin{aligned}
\text { Var } \quad & =\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N}\left(X_{j}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}}{N} \\
& =\frac{\sum(X-\bar{X})^{2}}{N}-\bar{X}^{2} \\
& =\frac{\sum X^{2}}{N}-\bar{X}^{2}
\end{aligned}$$

